Mineral Specimen Size Guide: Official Classification for ...
  URL: https://emineralogy.com/blog/mineral-specimen-size-guide/
  a miniature is typically classified as up to 6 cm, while a small cabinet specimen generally starts at 6 cm.

  --- Content ---
  # Mineral Specimen Size Guide: Official Classification for Collectors
  
  8 minutes read
  
  
  01/06/2025
  
  
  Jakub Velicka
  
  
  [Starting Collection](https://emineralogy.com/topic/starting-collection/)
  
  Collectors categorise minerals by size. Unfortunately, **there is no official guidance** that defines each size category precisely. To establish a consensus, we went through websites of major mineral dealers and [Tucson Gem and Mineral Show competition rules](https://hub.tgms.org/wp-content/uploads/2021/10/22-Competitives-Handbook.pdf "https://hub.tgms.org/wp-content/uploads/2021/10/22-Competitives-Handbook.pdf") to see what sizes they use and what dimensions they assign to each size.
  
  ![Different mineral specimen sizes](https://emineralogy.com/images/posts/2/main-photo-68434b10867c4.jpg)
  
  _**Photo:** Museum, Cabinet, Miniature and Thumbnail minerals in one photo_
  
  Some dealers made our job difficult, because as you will see later, they define size categories inconsistently - stating one limit but applying another. And the fact that the United States uses the imperial system instead of metric system doesn’t make it any easier - because converting inches to centimetres rarely gives round numbers. Here is a list of **generally accepted mineral size categories**:
  
  | Size Name | Minimum Size | Maximum Size |
  | --- | --- | --- |
  | Micromount | ? | ? |
  | Thumbnail | ? | ? |
  | Toenail | ? | ? |
  | Miniature | ? | ? |
  | Small Cabinet | ? | ? |
  | Cabinet | ? | ? |
  | Large Cabinet / Museum | ? | ? |
  
  Now, let’s look at the **dimensions for each size**. We went through hundreds of minerals, noted the size category assigned by dealers, and then compared it to the actual dimensions. So for example, if a dealer says thumbnails are up to 2.5 cm but then labels minerals up to 3 cm as thumbnails, we assume they consider anything up to 3 cm a thumbnail. I hope that makes sense.
  
  ## Micromount (up to 1 cm)
  
  The first and smallest mineral size. There is general agreement that a Micromount is a mineral specimen that doesn’t exceed 1 cm in any dimension. You can have stunning crystals, but to appreciate them, you often need magnification.
  
  ## Thumbnail (1 cm - 3 cm)
  
  Here we first encounter some disagreement. The original definition of the thumbnail size class was _thumbnail is any mineral that fits into a 1.25-inch Perky Box_. In metric terms, that means a square box with 3.175 cm sides. So technically, a mineral could exceed 3.175 cm in length, since the diagonal of the box is longer. However, dealers generally label minerals as thumbnails if they don’t exceed 3 cm in any dimension.
  
  ![Thumbnail minerals specimen collection](https://emineralogy.com/images/posts/2/top-view-68436eb668e72.jpg)
  
  _**Photo:** Thumbnail minerals collection featuring world class Rhodochrosites or pink Cobaltoan Calcite_
  
  Thumbnail-sized specimens have recently become a popular category for collectors. The advantage is that, compared to larger specimens, you can get perfect crystals at a reasonable price.
  
  ## Toenail (3 cm - 3.8 cm)
  
  This size was recently established by the Tucson Gem and Mineral Show competition. The intention is to cover specimens that are just slightly too large for thumbnails but too small to be classified as miniatures. I personally think this size is a bit redundant. In our shop, we label anything up to 3 cm as a thumbnail and anything above 3 cm as a miniature, which is the next size class.
  
  ## Miniature (3.8 cm - 6 cm)
  
  Another very popular category among collectors. Dealers generally claim “miniature” is up to 5 cm, but most label specimens up to 6 cm as miniatures. This probably comes from the fact that a 5 cm display box can actually accommodate a slightly larger specimen, thanks to its diagonal inner dimension.
  
  Some collectors even use a sub-category called “Small Miniature” (3 – 4.5 cm), but it feels a bit too much cluttered.
  
  ## Small Cabinet (6 cm - 10 cm)
  
  Here we are getting to minerals of proper size - cabinets. The first category is small cabinets—according to dealer labels, specimens up to 10 cm. Building a small-cabinet collection requires more display space, and quality pieces become noticeably more expensive.
  
  ## Cabinet (10 cm - 13 cm)
  
  Also in this category, there is not much consensus in the market. Some dealers or collectors extend “cabinet” up to 14 or even 15 cm. We’ve used the Tucson Gem and Mineral Show competition guidelines, which define cabinet size as _not larger than 5 inches (13 cm) in any dimension_.
  
  ## Large Cabinet / Museum (larger than 13 cm)
  
  The largest category of minerals. You’re far more likely to see these in museums than in personal collections. Displaying large-cabinet specimens often requires a dedicated room. Quality pieces in this size range are rare - and expensive.
  
  | Size Name | Minimum Size | Maximum Size |
  | --- | --- | --- |
  | Micromount | 0 cm | 1 cm |
  | Thumbnail | 1 cm | 3 cm |
  | Toenail | 3 cm | 3.8 cm |
  | Miniature | 3.8 cm | 6 cm |
  | Small Cabinet | 6 cm | 10 cm |
  | Cabinet | 10 cm | 13 cm |
  | Large Cabinet / Museum | 13 cm | N/A |
  
  Dimensions are borderline - for example, a **miniature** is typically classified as **up to 6 cm**, while a **small cabinet** specimen generally **starts at 6 cm**. Choosing the correct category always requires considering all three dimensions of the mineral.
  
  A specimen with its longest edge measuring 6 cm, but with the other two dimensions significantly smaller, would generally be classified as a miniature. In contrast, a specimen where all three dimensions are close to 6 cm would more likely be considered a small cabinet, due to its greater overall volume and presence.
  
  As you can see, classifying mineral sizes can be a bit tricky. Everyone uses slightly different measurements. But if you stick to the table we’ve created, you can’t go wrong. You’ll be aligned with the general market consensus!
  
